excerpt: City views spread from this 1700s observation tower, plus a camera obscura & 2 exhibition halls.
detail_description: Torre Tavira is a historic observation tower in Cadiz, dating back to the 18th century. It offers stunning panoramic views of the city and the sea, making it a must-visit for photography enthusiasts. The tower features a camera obscura on its top floor, projecting real-time images of the surroundings onto a white screen. Visitors can also explore two exhibition halls within the tower.
name: Torre Tavira
address: C. Marqués del Real Tesoro, 10, 11001 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Iconic beach with views of San Sebastián & Santa Catalina castles, plus nearby eateries & nightlife.
detail_description: La Caleta is one of the four beaches in Cadiz, but it stands out as the smallest and most popular due to its location next to the old town and between two castles. It gained pop-culture significance as a filming location for a scene in Die Another Day. Visitors can relax on its golden shores, visit the iconic Spa of Lady of Palma, and enjoy beach bars.
name: La Caleta

excerpt: Picturesque park known for its large array of plants & trees, plus paths & a lake with a waterfall
detail_description: Parque Genovés is a picturesque and expansive park located in the Old City section of Cadiz. It borders the university campus to the north and features a wide variety of plants, trees, and pathways. The park's design by Valencian architect Geronimo Genoves Puig includes a grotto with a waterfall and an ornamental lake adorned with dinosaur sculptures. Visitors can enjoy picnics, leisurely walks, or let children play at the playground.
name: Parque Genovés
address: Av. Dr. Gómez Ulla, s/n, 11003 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Stalls offer produce, meat & fish, household goods & more at this bustling market with a cafeteria.
detail_description: Mercado Central de Abastos de Cádiz is a bustling market offering a variety of goods, including produce, meat, fish, and household items. It is one of the oldest covered markets in Spain and is known for its seafood selection, featuring clams, winkles, mantis shrimps, murex, razor shells, moray eel and tuna. The market also houses a snail stall with live snails.
name: Mercado Central de Abastos de Cádiz
address: Pl. de la Libertad, S/N, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Former island fortress now a destination for historical exhibits, concerts & other cultural events.
detail_description: Located in Cadiz, Spain, Castillo de San Sebastian is a former island fortress that has been transformed into a hub for historical exhibits, concerts, and cultural events. The castle offers stunning views of the Atlantic and La Caleta beach. Visitors can take a leisurely stroll along the coast to reach Santa Catalina Castle, the oldest fortress in Cadiz.
name: Castillo de San Sebastian
address: GMHM+FH, P.º Fernando Quiñones, s/n, 11002 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Well-known town square known for its landmark historic buildings including a church & city hall.
detail_description: Plaza de San Juan de Dios is a popular public square recognized for its distinctive, notable edifices such as a cathedral and municipal government building. This town square displays an array of historical landmarks that are important to the local community. It is well-known for attracting tourists who enjoy experiencing the cultural significance of these iconic structures. The plaza's architecture showcases a blend of traditional and modern elements that make it an incredible sight to behold.
name: pl. de San Juan de Dios

excerpt: Museum in old Franciscan convent & modern building, known for its 17th-century Spanish collection.
detail_description: The Cadiz Museum is a combination of an old Franciscan convent and a modern building, housing an impressive 17th-century Spanish collection. The museum's history dates back to 1000 BC, making it one of Europe's oldest continuously inhabited cities. It has been occupied by various civilizations including the Phoenicians, Romans, and Arabs. The museum boasts a rich archaeological collection with artifacts from these ancient cultures.
name: Cadiz Museum
address: Pl. de Mina, s/n, 11004 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: 17th-century fortress complex with panoramic ocean vistas & exhibition space for modern art.
detail_description: The Castillo de Santa Catalina is a 17th-century fortress complex located in Cadiz, offering stunning panoramic views of the Atlantic Ocean and La Caleta beach. This historic landmark was constructed by Philip II as a response to the brief occupation of Cadiz by Anglo-Dutch forces in 1596. The castle now features exhibition spaces for modern art and hosts open-air concerts in its internal courtyard during the summer.
name: Castillo de Santa Catalina
address: C. Campo de las Balas, s/n, 11002 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Expansive beachfront close to the city center ringed by a wide promenade with cafes & bars.
detail_description: Playa de la Victoria is a vast beachfront area conveniently located near the city center, featuring a broad promenade lined with charming cafes and bars. The smart neighborhood surrounding the beach offers an enjoyable evening stroll, with opportunities to explore small shops and independent boutiques, as well as indulge in delightful dining experiences at renowned restaurants like Nahu Beach and Arsenio Manila.
name: Playa de la Victoria

detail_description: Located in the Plaza Fraguela in Cadiz, Gran Teatro Falla is a prominent theater built in 1886 after its predecessor was destroyed by fire. The building's neo-Mudejar style features colorful bricks and horseshoe arches on its facade. It stands alongside other historic structures like the neoclassical Carcel Real and Casa de las Viudas.
name: Gran Teatro Falla

excerpt: Cádiz is an ancient port city in the Andalucia region of southwestern Spain. The home of the Spanish Navy, the port boomed in the 16th-century as a base for exploration and trade. It has more than 100 watchtowers, including the iconic Torre Tavira, which was traditionally used for spotting ships. On the waterfront is the domed, 18th-century Cádiz Cathedral, featuring baroque and neoclassical elements.
detail_description: Cádiz, a historic port city in southwestern Spain, is known for its rich maritime heritage and stunning architecture. The city boasts over 100 watchtowers, including the famous Torre Tavira, once used for spotting ships. Its waterfront is graced by the elegant Cádiz Cathedral, a striking example of baroque and neoclassical design.
name: Cádiz

excerpt: Laid-back La Viña is a traditional fisherman’s quarter, where buzzing Andalusian taverns and tapas bars serve regional fino sherries and grilled razor clams. Every year, vibrant carnival celebrations take place in quaint squares like Plaza Tío de la Tiza and along narrow streets lined with colorful townhouses. A small garden overlooking La Caleta beach is shaded by the Arbol del Mora, a long-standing mulberry tree.
detail_description: La Viña is a charming traditional fisherman's neighborhood in Cadiz, known for its lively Andalusian taverns and tapas bars serving regional fino sherries and grilled razor clams. The area hosts vibrant carnival celebrations in picturesque squares like Plaza Tío de la Tiza and along colorful streets lined with townhouses. Visitors can relax in a small garden overlooking La Caleta beach shaded by the Arbol del Mora, a historic mulberry tree.
name: La Viña

excerpt: Church dating from 1719, with a rococo-era altarpiece & a famed painting by Spanish artist Murillo.
detail_description: The Iglesia del Oratorio de San Felipe Neri, a church dating back to 1719, is a Baroque masterpiece located in Cadiz. The church houses the renowned rococo-era altarpiece and features an acclaimed painting by Spanish artist Murillo. Additionally, it holds historical significance as the headquarters of the historic 1812 Courts of Cadiz where Spain's first constitution, known as La Pepa, was drafted.
name: Iglesia del Oratorio de San Felipe Neri

excerpt: Cobblestone street lined with trees & ornamental lampposts & offering sweeping ocean views.
detail_description: Alameda Apodaca is a charming park located in Cadiz, featuring cobblestone streets lined with trees and ornamental lampposts that offer sweeping ocean views. The park is adorned with numerous trees, fountains, wrought iron lamp posts, sculptures, colorful ceramic benches, and checkerboard tiles. Visitors can enjoy the tranquility and relaxation of the sea while strolling through this beautiful park.
name: Alameda Apodaca

excerpt: 18th century marble monument added to the city walls that divide the old & new parts of the city.
detail_description: Puertas de Tierra is an 18th-century marble monument located at the entrance of Cadiz, dividing the old and new parts of the city. It stands as a remnant of the city's defensive walls and is now situated in the middle of a road, making it a bit challenging to capture in photos. However, it remains an impressive sight from a distance.
name: Puertas de Tierra

excerpt: Restaurant serving up plates of fried seafood, fish dishes & octopus salad at sidewalk tables.
detail_description: Located in the heart of Cadiz's flower market, Freiduria Marisquería Las Flores 1 is a popular spot offering a variety of fried seafood and fish dishes. The restaurant features sidewalk tables where patrons can savor plates of mixed seafood fry, anchovies, shrimps, prawns, octopus salad, calamari strips, marinated dogfish, paella and fideua at affordable prices.
name: Freiduria Marisquería Las Flores 1

detail_description: When visiting Cadiz, make sure to explore Plaza de España, a significant square in the city. The main attraction here is a grand monument that commemorates the signing of Spain's first constitution in 1812. As you stroll through the area, take note of other notable landmarks such as San Juan de Dios and Plaza de San Antonio. The Monument to the Constitution of 1812, also known as Monumento a las Cortes, is a must-see at Plaza de España.
name: Plaza de España

detail_description: Plaza de España has undergone a transformation with its complete pedestrianization, making it much more enjoyable for strolling. The monument to the Constitution and surrounding buildings are now more prominent, enhancing the beauty of the square. While some may find it noisy, many visitors appreciate its stunning and pleasant atmosphere.
name: Pl. de España

excerpt: Cathedral featuring baroque, rococo & neoclassical styles with a bell-tower climb to dramatic views.
detail_description: Catedral de Cádiz is a stunning architectural masterpiece that showcases baroque, rococo, and neoclassical styles. It took 110 years to build and stands as a symbol of the city's resilience after being decimated in the 16th century. The cathedral's gold dome dominates the neighborhood, offering dramatic views from its bell tower climb.
name: Catedral de Cádiz

excerpt: Partially excavated ancient ruins of a massive Roman theater that held 20,000 spectators.
detail_description: The Teatro Romano de Cádiz, also known as Balbi Theatre, is an ancient Roman theater dating back to 70 BC. Discovered in 1980 in the El Populo district of Cadiz, it is one of the largest and oldest Roman theaters found in the Iberian Peninsula. The theater was built by Lucius Cornelius Balbus, an advisor to Julius Caesar, and his nephew.
name: Teatro Romano de Cádiz

excerpt: Formed around 2 chapels, this Christian oratory dates to around 1730 & is filled with art.
detail_description: Oratorio de la Santa Cueva is a Christian oratory in Cadiz, Spain, dating back to around 1730. It consists of two chapels and is adorned with beautiful art. Despite its unassuming facade, this oratory holds historical significance as it belonged to the Spiritual Withdrawal Congregation in the 18th century. The Museum of Cadiz nearby offers insights into the city's history and features works by renowned artists like Murillo and Rubens.
name: Oratorio de la Santa Cueva

excerpt: This small, relaxed museum offers a collection of puppets from around the world & history exhibits.
detail_description: Museo del Títere, located in Cadiz, Spain, is a small yet captivating museum that showcases an extensive collection of puppets from various cultures worldwide. Visitors can explore the history of puppetry through guided tours and exhibits featuring intricately handcrafted puppets with their own unique backstories. The museum also offers insight into the art of puppet-making through workshops and a library dedicated to this traditional craft.
name: Museo del Títere
address: Puertas de Tierra, Bóvedas de Santa Elena, s/n, 11006 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Fortress built in 1672 as part of the sea wall, now a venue for concerts & exhibitions.
detail_description: Baluarte de la Candelaria, a fortress built in 1672 as part of the sea wall, has transformed from a defensive structure to a cultural venue. It hosts concerts and temporary exhibitions throughout the year. The surrounding area is rich in historical landmarks such as palaces, ancient buildings like Teatro Romano, and old quarters with stunning architecture. Additionally, visitors can explore museums that showcase Cadiz's rich history.
name: Baluarte de la Candelaria
address: Alameda Hermanas Carvia Bernal, 6, 11003 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Old-town core El Pópulo is dominated by the towering, baroque Cádiz Cathedral and its older, smaller neighbor, Santa Cruz church. The ancient Roman Theatre is now an open-air museum of excavated ruins, while the striking Arco de los Blanco is one of several atmospheric medieval passageways. Narrow streets lined with leather shops and tapas bars open onto grand plazas where crowds eat on lively restaurant terraces.
detail_description: El Pópulo, the oldest neighborhood in Cadiz, is a captivating labyrinth of narrow streets and timeless allure that beckons travelers with its rich history and lively nightlife. During the day, visitors can meander through its cobblestone lanes flanked by centuries-old structures, where weathered exteriors echo stories of days gone by.
name: El Pópulo

detail_description: Experience the perfect way to end your day with a leisurely stroll along Av. Campo del Sur, where you can enjoy stunning views of the seafront and witness breathtaking sunsets with the iconic Cathedral as a backdrop.
name: Av. Campo del Sur

detail_description: Mercado Central, located inside a former convent, is a bustling marketplace where you can experience the lively workday atmosphere. The counters are adorned with hanging chorizo and jamon while expert hands slice ham razor thin. Fresh squid is cleaned of its ink and displayed on beds of crushed ice. It's a great spot to grab a bite and soak in the local culture. Additionally, it offers one of the best views of the Cathedral and sea wall, making it an ideal stop for tourists.
name: Mercado Central

excerpt: Completed in 1929, this monument & its statues commemorate the Constitution of 1812.
name: The 1812 Constitution Monument

excerpt: Snug parish church featuring an airy, rustic sanctuary & domed roof in a charming seaside locale.
detail_description: The Church Santa Cruz, also known as the Old Cadiz Cathedral, is a charming parish church located in the seaside city of Cadiz. The church features an airy and rustic sanctuary with a domed roof, adding to its quaint appeal.
name: Church Santa Cruz (Old Cadiz Cathedral)

excerpt: Local history museum containing many articles from Napoleon's siege of the city between 1810 & 1820.
detail_description: The Museo de las Cortes de Cádiz, also known as the Cadiz Court Museum, is a local history museum that opened in 1912 to commemorate the centenary of the first Spanish Constitution. It houses a diverse collection of artifacts and documents from the 18th and 19th centuries, with a particular focus on Napoleon's siege of Cadiz between 1810 and 1812.
name: Museo de las Cortes de Cádiz

detail_description: Iglesia de Santiago Apóstol, also known as the Baroque Santiago Church or the Church of Santiago, is a 17th-century church located next to Cadiz Cathedral. Originally built in the 16th century and later reconstructed due to damage, this small church boasts a beautiful exterior and an impressive interior with magnificent sculpture work and beautifully carved wood altars.
name: Iglesia de Santiago Apóstol

detail_description: Plaza de la Catedral, one of the various charming squares in Cadiz, is an ideal spot to relax and enjoy a cup of coffee or tapas. It serves as a perfect resting place after hours of exploring the town, allowing visitors to soak in the lively ambiance while observing people going about their daily activities.
name: Plaza de la Catedral

detail_description: Iglesia de Santa María is a significant religious site in Cadiz, housing the most devotional image in the city with a rich history. The brotherhood mass, particularly on Friday afternoons, comes highly recommended. The church also holds the beloved image of the Nazarene and other well-cared-for sculptures that are considered some of the most beautiful in the world. Additionally, it is home to one of the most revered images in the neighborhood, affectionately known as el Grenuo.
name: Iglesia de Santa María
address: C/ Santa María, s/n, Capilla de Jesús Nazareno, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

detail_description: Jardines de Alameda Apodaca is a picturesque landscaped walkway in Cadiz, running parallel to the sea from the walls of San Carlos to the Baluarte de la Candelaria. This 18th-century walk consists of three streets divided by rows of trees and features intriguing sculptures. The park offers mosaic benches, extraordinary plant species, and a wide promenade paved with different patterned plates.
name: Jardines de Alameda Apodaca

excerpt: Refined Spanish dishes using Cadiz produce in a sumptuous 1912 room with arches, frescoes & gilt.
detail_description: Restaurante Café Royalty in Cádiz offers a refined dining experience in a grand salon that dates back to 1912. The recently restored rococo-style restaurant serves up four courses of Andalusian cuisine, featuring dishes made with local produce. This historic establishment was once frequented by intellectuals, artists, and politicians before it closed during the Spanish Civil War. The café exudes an old-world charm and is also a great spot for tea or coffee accompanied by delectable cakes.
name: Restaurante Café Royalty - Restaurantes en Cádiz

detail_description: Explore Cadiz in a unique way by joining one of the city's bike tours. Knowledgeable guides like Marina and Ana will lead you through both the new and old parts of Cadiz, sharing historical insights along the way. If biking isn't your style, consider renting a scooter for a day to cover more ground and receive local recommendations on where to go. The experience is highly recommended for first-time visitors looking for an exciting way to discover the city.
name: Cadizfornia tours Ebikes, Segways, walking tours, day trips
address: Calle Sopranis núm. 9 - Local 1, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: 650-m long urban beach with a first aid station & marina, plus lifeguards, showers & sunbed rentals.
detail_description: Playa Santa María del Mar is a 650-meter long urban beach located in Cadiz, offering a first aid station, marina, lifeguards, showers, and sunbed rentals. It is known for its idyllic setting and necessary amenities such as showers, toilets, and dining options. The beach is easily accessible from the port of Cadiz and boasts a wide expanse with warm waters suitable for swimming.
name: Playa Santa María del Mar

detail_description: Iglesia Parroquial de San Antonio is a charming discovery in Cadiz, dating back to the 17th century. It is situated in a plaza that shares its name, adding to its allure. The church's exterior is described as majestic and beautiful, attracting both locals and foreigners. While it may be hidden, it captivates visitors with its spaciousness and excellent location. Although not explored inside by some, the church remains an impressive sight for all who come across it.
name: Iglesia Parroquial de San Antonio

detail_description: Playa de Santa María del Mar in Cádiz offers a quality gastronomic experience with a concept called #PiacereOriginale. The restaurant provides a comfortable and elegant atmosphere, capturing the passion for decoration inspired by The Godfather and Italian culture. It features a spacious interior space along with a terrace of over 70 square meters, accommodating more than a hundred diners.
name: Playa de Santa María del Mar (Cádiz)

detail_description: Iglesia de San Juan de Dios is a beautiful church located in the historic Barrio del Populo area of Cadiz. The plaza where it stands has been the heart of the city since the 16th century, making it an ideal starting point for exploring this ancient city. The church, housed in a former hospital building, boasts stunning interior decorations and is well worth a visit despite its unassuming exterior.
name: Iglesia de San Juan de Dios
address: pl. de San Juan de Dios, 1, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

detail_description: The Catacumbas del Beaterio in Cadiz is a 17th-century underground burial site originally used by Franciscan friars to bury lay sisters. The catacombs survived an explosion that destroyed the building above them in the mid-19th century and are now open for tours. Visitors can explore the underground gallery, six meters below ground, adorned with engravings and drawings. Historical objects and war weapons found in the area are also on display.
name: Catacumbas del Beaterio
Yacimiento Arqueológico Casa del Obispo
address: Plaza Fray Felix s/n, Callejón Arquillo del Obispo s/n, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: This 3,900-m. gold-sand beach features dunes, plus wildlife including gulls & lizards.
detail_description: Playa de La Cortadura is a 3,900-meter golden sandy beach with dunes and diverse wildlife such as gulls and lizards. The coastal area between Cortadura and la Barrosa, along with the marshes of Sancti Petri, Trocaderos, and los Torunos are captivating land areas. The salt flats covering over 5,500 hectares have been utilized since Phoenician times.
name: Playa de La Cortadura
address: Av. Vía Augusta Julia, 3, 11011 Cádiz, Spain

detail_description: Balneario de la Palma, situated in Cadiz, Spain, is a charming spa town renowned for its picturesque beaches, clear waters, and verdant surroundings. It offers an array of leisure pursuits including swimming, sunbathing, and perusing the diverse range of shops and eateries within the town.
name: Balneario de la Palma
address: Av. Duque de Nájera, 11002 Cádiz, Spain

name: Plaza de San Juan de Dios
address: pl. de San Juan de Dios, 1, 11005 Cádiz, Spain

detail_description: Playa La Caleta is located in Cadiz, a historic town founded by the Phoenicians in 1100BC. This ancient settlement, one of the oldest in Europe, is situated on a narrow strip of land almost entirely surrounded by water. The old city features charming narrow alleys with impressive architectural designs and is home to several sandy beaches, including Playa La Caleta.
name: Playa La Caleta

detail_description: Tirabuzón is a charming beachfront cafeteria located on the Santa Maria del Mar Beach in Cadiz. It offers stunning views of the old town and the sea, making it an ideal spot to enjoy a beautiful sunset. The establishment is praised for its friendly staff, excellent service, and a diverse menu featuring both national and international cuisine. Visitors can indulge in delicious cocktails and beer while taking in the picturesque surroundings.
name: Tirabuzón
address: Av. Alcalde Manuel de la Pinta, 11E, 11008 Cádiz, Spain

detail_description: El Corte Inglés Bahía de Cádiz is a shopping paradise that caters to all your retail needs under one expansive roof. This massive department store features an impressive array of products, from clothing and accessories to gourmet food items available at the attached Hipercor supermarket. While prices may be on the higher side, the convenience of finding everything in one location makes it a go-to spot for tourists pressed for time.
name: El Corte Inglés Bahía de Cádiz
address: Av. las Cortes de Cádiz, 1, 11012 Cádiz, Spain

excerpt: Cathedral-affiliated artifacts, ancient books & paintings in a separate building with a courtyard.
detail_description: Nestled just a stone's throw from the majestic Cadiz Cathedral, the Casa de la Contaduría, also known as the Museo Catedralicio, is a hidden gem that beckons history enthusiasts. This charming museum showcases an impressive collection of artifacts linked to the cathedral, including exquisite paintings and intricate sculptures crafted from ivory. Visitors can marvel at stunning gold and silver works dating back to the 17th and 18th centuries.
name: Casa de la Contaduría | Museo Catedralicio

excerpt: Archaeological museum with artifacts & exhibits on ancient Phoenician culture & civilization.
detail_description: Yacimiento Arqueológico Gadir is a must-visit in Cadiz, offering insights into the ancient Phoenician culture and civilization. Situated near Mercado de las Flores, it shares space with Museo de los Titeres. The site showcases the oldest archaeological remains of the western Mediterranean, including two blocks and eight houses from the ancient Phoenician city, along with human remains and exhibitions.
name: Yacimiento Arqueológico Gadir
